SIMPLE: preen
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Preen
<hw>Preen</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>pre⟦oacute⟧n</ets> a clasp, bodkin; akin to D. <ets>priem</ets>
punch, bodkin, awl, G. <ets>pfriem</ets>, Icel. <ets>prj⟦omac⟧nn</ets> a
knitting needle, pin, Dan. <ets>preen</ets> a bodkin, punch.]</ety>
<def>A forked tool used by clothiers in dressing cloth.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Preen</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Preen
<hw>Preen</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Preened</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Preening</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[See <er>Preen</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>; or cf. <er>Prune</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To dress
with, or as with, a preen; to trim or dress with the beak, as the
feathers; -- said of birds.</def> <rj><au>Derham.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To trim up, as trees.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>Halliwell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>To dress (oneself) carefully
or stylishly; to primp.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To pride (oneself) on one's accomplishments; to
congratulate (oneself).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Preen</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Preen
<hw>Preen</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To dress up neatly and smartly; to
make oneself well-groomed and well-dressed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To feel proud of one's achievement; to swell or
gloat.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Preengage</ent>⟦br⟧
